To maintain the Single Responsibility Principle, you should create a new class titled `PlaylistManager` or `QueueManager`. This class will be responsible for the logic of organizing songs based on priority, keeping the `MediaPlayer` focused strictly on playback and the `Song` class focused on data.

The `PlaylistManager` will manage the internal queues and provide a single ordered queue for the `MediaPlayer` to consume.

### Step-by-step implementation:

1.  **Create `PlaylistManager`**: This class will contain two internal queues (e.g., `highPriority` and `lowPriority`).
2.  **Add `addSong` method**: This method will evaluate the `Song` priority level and route it to the appropriate internal queue.
3.  **Add `getCompleteQueue` method**: This method merges the queues (prioritizing high-priority ones) into a single queue that the `MediaPlayer` can process.

```java
package umg.edu.gt.model;

import umg.edu.gt.data_structure.queue.manual.QueueLinked;

public class PlaylistManager {
    private QueueLinked<Song> highPriorityQueue = new QueueLinked<>();
    private QueueLinked<Song> normalPriorityQueue = new QueueLinked<>();

    public void addSong(Song song) {
        // Assuming priority 1 is high and 2 is normal
        if (song.getPriority() == 1) {
            highPriorityQueue.enqueue(song);
        } else {
            normalPriorityQueue.enqueue(song);
        }
    }

    public QueueLinked<Song> getOrderedQueue() {
        QueueLinked<Song> orderedQueue = new QueueLinked<>();

        while (!highPriorityQueue.isEmpty()) {
            orderedQueue.enqueue(highPriorityQueue.dequeue());
        }

        while (!normalPriorityQueue.isEmpty()) {
            orderedQueue.enqueue(normalPriorityQueue.dequeue());
        }

        return orderedQueue;
    }
}
```

